          "body": "The psalm closes with an explicit purpose clause and a vow: 'That my soul may sing praise to You and not be silent. O Lord my God, I will give thanks to You forever' (30:12). The purpose clause (*lema'an*) names the goal of the entire reversal: *so that praise may continue*. The transformation of verse 11 did not happen for David's comfort alone; it happened so that God's faithfulness would have a voice. The *olam* of verse 12 — 'forever' — answers the *chay* of verse 5: God's favor spans a lifetime; David's praise will span eternity. The psalm that began with a past-tense rescue ends with a future-tense vow. This is the movement of all true thanksgiving: from 'You have done' to 'I will praise.' The silence that would have followed death (v. 9) is replaced by a praise that will never end. The congregation summoned in verse 4 now has the theological and biographical grounds to join that praise permanently."
