        "excerpt": "For His anger is but for a moment, His favor is for a lifetime; weeping may last for the night, but a shout of joy comes in the morning.",
        "body": "After three verses of first-person testimony, David suddenly pivots to address the congregation and to offer a theological generalization. The pivot is significant: David cannot keep the rescue to himself. The *chasidim* — the covenant faithful, those characterized by *chesed* — are summoned to sing (*zamar*) and to give thanks to God's holy name (*qodesh zekher*, his 'holy memorial-name,' the name that recalls His covenant acts). The move from 'I was rescued' to 'you must praise' is the natural movement of biblical testimony.\n\nThe grounds for the summons are stated in verse 5, and they are grounded in God's character, not in David's experience. 'For His anger is but for a moment; His favor is for a lifetime.' This verse has been variously interpreted as referring to God's disciplinary anger toward His own people (the Reformed reading, following Calvin: God's corrective chastisement is purposive and time-limited) or as a general statement about the contrast between divine patience and divine wrath (the broader reading). Both readings are canonical. The Psalter's own framing favors the first: God's anger here is the anger of discipline applied to His servant (compare Psalm 103:8-13; Hebrews 12:5-11), not the eschatological wrath poured out on His enemies.\n\nThe night-and-morning image of verse 5 is among the most pastorally enduring in the Old Testament. Weeping (*bekhi*) 'lodges for the night' — the verb *lun* is the ordinary word for a traveler spending the night at an inn. Sorrow is a temporary resident, not a permanent inhabitant. Joy (*rinnah*, a shout or cry of joy) comes 'in the morning.' The morning is not a metaphor for optimism; it is the covenant-historical dawn — the point at which God's intervention reverses the night. Charles Spurgeon in *The Treasury of David* notes that the morning-joy of verse 5 is the interpretive key to every night of suffering the believer endures: 'The night is short; the morning is certain; the joy is divine.'\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rega* (moment, v.5) — a flash, an instant; root means to be still, to be quiet, emphasizing the brevity rather than the intensity. *Ratson* (favor, v.5) — God's good pleasure, delight, acceptance; appears twice in the psalm (vv.5, 7). *Bekhi* (weeping) + *lun* (lodge for the night) — the combination is vivid: grief as overnight guest. *Rinnah* (shout of joy, v.5) — the ringing cry of celebratory joy, often used of liturgical praise (Psalm 47:1; 98:4)."
